I&#39;m in the process of working on an experiment in competitive
coevolution for my MS thesis work. My first step is to recreate
(relatively closely) Ken Stanley&#39;s original competitive coevolution
robot duel experiment, which is where I am at now. This is my first
real project with NEAT, so I&#39;m probably messing up some pretty basic
stuff.

Now that I can run the experiment, I&#39;m seeing my first problems. I&#39;m
not seeing nearly enough complexification compared to the original
experiment. I figure a good chunk of that is my parameters need
tweaking, but I could also be missing something essential in my
implementation.

I have 10 runs, and all seemed to do rather poorly:
Average of 7.9 dominant strategies
Final dominant strategies have an average of 0.3 hidden nodes
Final dominant strategies have an average of 43.6 connections

Similarly to Ken&#39;s original experiment, I have 500 generations, with
two teams (red and blue) with 256 robots per team. Each generation
each robot competes in 24 matches (both left and right starts against
4 best agents from the other team, and 8 randomly selected
hall-of-famers).

The team champs compete in a tournament against each other to figure
out which is the generation champ. I differ slightly from the original
experiment as I only have them compete in 158 matches (79 food
configurations, with both left and right starts). If they tie, I
randomly select one to be the generation champ (not sure if this is
how it wad done in the original experiment).

The generation champ them plays all prior dominant strategies in the
same style tournament, and if it defeats them all, it is the newest
dominant strategy (ties are counted as a loss, not sure if this is the
same as the original experiment).

My implementation is highly multi-threaded, written in C++ for Linux
(I have lots of multicore linux boxes I can use at work). The
underlying NEAT implementation is basically a Linux port of Mat
Buckland&#39;s implementation from his gaming AI book, extended a bit here
and there, particularly to support neural net duplication to support
safe multi-threading.

All the experimental stuff is in the
competitiveCoevolutionNeatMain.cpp file. There are two threads defined
in there, the runJobManagerThread (of which only 1 is run), and the
runExecutionThread (of which any number will run based on parameters).
All the NEAT stuff is encapsulated in classes, with most work going
through the higher level Cga class.

I&#39;m attaching a tarball of my source code (it&#39;s a work in progress and
pretty rough), and my spreadsheet with my 10 run results (summary
sheet, and then a sheet for each run with the name of the machine I
used).

All the data in the spreadsheet is from the .csv files in the
dataFiles directory in the tarball.


Parameters are found in the parameters.h file, but here are the values
